            <div type="commentary" xml:lang="en">
                <p>The text Δι(ο)νυσο - the name of god Dionysos in the genitive allows us to identify it as a dedicatory inscription in the form 
                    of ownership insciription where the owner is a god - a common form of cultic graffiti. Placement on the underside is also common for such
                    graffiti. Dionysos was worshipped in Berezan (location?) and Olbia (location). Known from dedications... 
                The context of find is... Omission of omicron is/not a local feature? just a mistake? 
                Inv. Card supplies the reading made by Krasotkinа, Bilimovich under the supervision of I.I. Tolstoy: Δι(ο)νύσ̣ο̣ - To Dionysos.
                LSJ, s.v. Dιόνυσος lists alternative spellings of the name in epigraphic sources, including Δίνυσος Αρχ. Εφ. 1913.221 (Mytilene). 
                This comparandum may point to a Lesbian dedicator in Berezan? Other: Διένυσος, IG 12(7).78 (Amorgos); Δεύνυσος, Διώνουσος - Boeotia, IG 7.2468.
                </p>
            </div>
